Anderson has been elite this season and can be counted as a DL1 option despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Baltimore Ravens on Christmas Day.

Madubuike showed up in Week 16, tallying four solos, three assists, 0.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. Nnamdi took a massive step back since inking his extension and going back to his given name, but games like this remind us of his upside. Still, Madubuike is more DL3 than DL2 for Week 17, even if he will be plugged in as a DT1 due to a lack of comparable options. Start Madubuike as a DT1/DL3 for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Baun was excellent in Week 16, racking up seven solos, four assists, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Baun has produced at an elite level all season and is a top-three option for Week 17. Start him everywhere.

Elliss was excellent in Week 16, racking up two solos, five assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Kaden has been showing off his pass rushing skills of late, tallying a sack in four consecutive games. Elliss played some edge in New Orleans, so this is indeed part of his skill set. Tap Elliss as an upside LB2 play for the Week 17 matchup against Washington.

Warner was excellent in Week 16, racking up six solos and five assists against the Miami Dolphins. Warner is an obvious LB1 talent but had been producing at an LB3/4 level for a four week stretch before finally waking up in Week 15. Tap Warner as an LB1/2 option as opposed to a locked-in top-10 play.

Bernard was excellent in Week 16, tacking up eight solos and four assists against the New England Patriots. Bernard is starting to heat up at the right time but remains an LB2 option for Week 17. Start Bernard if you got him.

Brooks was excellent in Week 16, racking up four solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Brooks has been on fire for the Dolphins and can be counted as a top-15 option for Week 17, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Wagner was excellent in Week 16, tallying eight solos, one assist, and one pass defended. Wagner had two quiet weeks in a row, so a return to his LB1 form is a welcomed sign with championships on the line in Week 17. Fire Wagner up as a LB1 play for Week 17 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Henley was excellent in Week 16, tallying seven solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Henley has transformed into one of the most consistent options in the league and can be counted as a sa top-15 play for Week 17, thanks to a plus matchup against the New England Patriots.

Lavonte was excellent in Week 16, tallying seven solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss. David has been on fire recently, forcing his way back into the LB1 conversation. Treat him as one for Week 17 despite the neutral at best matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Nakobe was excellent in Week 16, tallying six solos and six assists. Nakobe has cemented himself as an LB1 option for years to come and should be treated as one for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Cashman rewarded fantasy managers who stuck with him despite the tough on-paper matchup, going off for mie solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Cashman has caught fire and should be treated as a top-15 option for Week 17 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Green Bay Packers. Add and start Cashman everywhere.

Luvu was excellent in Week 16, racking up three solos, four assists, two tackles for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Luvu bounced back from his worst fantasy output of the season to post his third-highest of the campaign. Luvu had been on fire prior to the Week 15 stinker and should be trusted as an LB2 option for Week 17, despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Hicks showed up again in Week 16, racking up seven solos and two assists. Hicks has officially caught fire for the Browns, and while he has not had any massive spike weeks, he still has recorded one in four of his last five games. Hicks is an LB3 with LB2 upside for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Miami Dolphins. Add Hicks where possible, even if it is just to block your opponent.

Kyzir was excellent in Week 16, reeling off five solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Kyzir has been on a mini heater for fantasy managers and makes for a sneaky LB2 option for Week 17, despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

To'oTo'o was excellent in Week 16, racking up five solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Henry is starting to heat up for the Texans and will get the start in Week 17 with Azeez Al-Shaair sidelined for at least one more week. To'oTo'o has been inconsistent this season and has picked up the production and heads into Week 17 with a plus matchup on tap against the Baltimore Ravens. Start To'oTo'o where needed.

Harris was excellent in Week 16, tallying five solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Harris is set to get another start this week with Azeez Al-Shaair serving the last game of his suspension and should be on rosters where needed, even if it is just as injury depth for someone like Eric Kendricks. Add and start Harris as an LB3 with LB2 upside for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Dual eligibility too? Jaylon saw an expanded role in Week 16 and responded with six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Carlies saw extra snaps due to E.J. Speed being ruled out with a knee injury and could be in line for a start this week if Speed is unable to return for next Sunday's matchup against the New York Giants. Jaylon is a smooth LB3 play for Week 17 if Speed is out. Deep leaguers should make the speculative add where possible.

Darius Muasau was solid in Week 16, tallying four solos, seven assists, and one tackle for loss. Bobby Okereke missed practice all of last week with a back injury and has little reason to return until he is fully healed in what was always expected to be a lost season for the New York Giants. This means Muasau should continue to start for New York, making him an LB3 option for Week 17, despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Indianapolis Colts. Add Muasau where needed.

Dee Winters was solid in Week 16, tallying six solos, two assista, and one pass defended. Winters is enjoying an expanded role with De'Vondre Campbell off the team due to a very public dispute over his reduced role and is a deep league injury replacement option for those who may have a player listed as questionable heading into Sunday. The 49ers play on Monday night, making him excellent emergency insurance provided he makes it through the practice week without a questionable tag of his own due to the chest injury he suffered. Keep Winters on the radar.

Windmon impressed in Week 16, racking up four solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. WIndmon saw an expanded role with Trevin Wallace (knee) lost for the year and should get another start in Week 17. The production was roster-worthy, but hopefully, no one is in a position where they will actually want to start someone who played just two defensive snaps all year prior to his Week 16 injury-fueled breakout. Still, Windmon is an option for those in 16+ team 11 v 11 leagues; for all others, he is bench depth at best. Be intrigued, but don't look to start Windmon unless absolutely necessary. Look elsewhere for your Week 17 LB4/5/flex2.

Van Noy has caught fire for the Ravens, most recently notching two solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Van Noy has recorded a sack in three of his last four games and can be counted as a DL2 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Houston Texans. Add Van Noy where available.

Gray was excellent in Week 16, tallying nine solos and six assists against the Indianapolis Colts. Gray got the start with Kenneth Murray (hamstring), Jack Gibbens (ankle), Luke Gifford (concussion), and more sidelined and will get another start this week if Gifford does not get cleared from the league's concussion protocol. A Gifford return would complicate things, so keep Gray as a speculative play until the final injury report on Friday. There is a strong chance that Gray has earned himself another start if Murray remains sidelined, even if Gifford returns, so make the stash where possible. Gray will be an LB3 option if gets the start, thanks to a plus matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.
